<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-19T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-19T14:00:00-05:00" n="890" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d890">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">800.0146/9–2044: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-20T02:00:00+07:00">September 20,
                                1944—2 a.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 10:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1587. Civil administration of liberated areas. Department’s 1219, September
                        16 crossed our 1581, September 19. As indicated in latter, Embassy proposes
                        to let matter rest until it receives further anticipated approach by Foreign
                        Office.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
            </body></text></TEI>